body: Is your input is valid? 125 in the right values with a zero point of -26 gives a value of 151, which exceeds the maximum for int8. Depending on when a cast to int32 happens that may or may not wrap around. If I change that to -125 the output from numpy and ORT are the same.

However if I change right[0,2] from 125 to 100, which with a zero point of -26 should be a valid int8 of 126 I do see a diff between numpy and ORT for two values. No diff if right[0,2] is 99.

@tracysh is this expected from MlaGemmBatch?

```
Numpy
[[ 12100   1951  35314]
 [ 11745   2293  36276]
 [ 18030 -10919  33648]]
ORT
[[ 12100   1951  35314]
 [ 11745   2293  36107]
 [ 18030 -10919  33515]]
```

But if we look at the matrix A from the onnx example, we will see that after subtracting a_zero_point we get values less than 0, which in turn is not within the limits of uint8 and this is correct.

[ONNX docs example](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators.md#examples-67)

If we first subtract and then cast to int32, then the answer will be incorrect.

```
import numpy as np

A = np.array([[11, 7, 3],
    [10, 6, 2],
    [9, 5, 1],
    [8, 4, 0], ], dtype=np.uint8)

a_zero_point = np.array([12], dtype=np.uint8)

B = np.array([[1, 4],
    [2, 5],
    [3, 6], ], dtype=np.uint8)

b_zero_point = np.array([0], dtype=np.uint8)


A_with_zero = (A - a_zero_point).astype(np.int32)
B_with_zero = (B - b_zero_point).astype(np.int32)

output = np.matmul(A_with_zero, B_with_zero)

expect_output = np.array([[-38, -83],
    [-44, -98],
    [-50, -113],
    [-56, -128], ], dtype=np.int32)
```

Outputs:
```
output = [[1498 3757]
 [1492 3742]
 [1486 3727]
 [1480 3712]]

expect_output = [[ -38  -83]
 [ -44  -98]
 [ -50 -113]
 [ -56 -128]]
```

But if we first cast to int32, and then start all the calculations, then we will get the correct answer.
```
import numpy as np

A = np.array([[11, 7, 3],
    [10, 6, 2],
    [9, 5, 1],
    [8, 4, 0], ], dtype=np.uint8)

a_zero_point = np.array([12], dtype=np.uint8)

B = np.array([[1, 4],
    [2, 5],
    [3, 6], ], dtype=np.uint8)

b_zero_point = np.array([0], dtype=np.uint8)


A_with_zero = A.astype(np.int32) - a_zero_point.astype(np.int32)
B_with_zero = B.astype(np.int32) - b_zero_point.astype(np.int32)

output = np.matmul(A_with_zero, B_with_zero)

expect_output = np.array([[-38, -83],
    [-44, -98],
    [-50, -113],
    [-56, -128], ], dtype=np.int32)
```

Outputs:
```
output = [[ -38  -83]
 [ -44  -98]
 [ -50 -113]
 [ -56 -128]]

expect_output = [[ -38  -83]
 [ -44  -98]
 [ -50 -113]
 [ -56 -128]]
```

@cupertank, we are using  [VPMADDUBSW](urlhttps://en.wikichip.org/wiki/x86/avx512_vnni) for Matrix A(uint8) and Matrix B(int8) on avx2 cpu. It overflows when numbers from both matrix A and matrix B are large, i.e., a1*b1 + a2*b2 > 2^15 or <=-2^15. That is your case.
In real model, this is seldom hit. If you hit, you can either chose to use [reduce_range ](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/8e3cdf0452f333fa1fe13a84770d1c9c7591b097/onnxruntime/python/tools/quantization/quantize.py#L232)quantization option to quantize the model or use u8u8 format(Matrix A uint8 and Matrix B uint8) mitigate this issue.

@yufenglee Well, in the case of real models, we have this "seldom" hit for almost any model we check. Specifically, almost all GPT-like models we have behave incorrectly. Do you have any probabilistic models that prove that such problems are actually "seldom"? What is the expected frequency of incorrect multiplications? 

Otherwise, it looks like ONNX can just randomly produce incorrect results in the very basic multiplication operation and I am just unsure how we should rely on the runtime at all.

@TanVD, how did you quantize your model? It's a tradeoff. VPMADDUBSW can get better performance but has overflow issue. To get exact result, you can use the u8u8 format that I mentioned, or quantize the model with reduce_range.
